## check levels of party after conversion to factor
levels(factor(df$party))
## [1] "D" "I" "R"
# rename part names and filter the state where user put in and shows first name, last name and party. 
# concatenate first name, last name and party and then put those strings in the message
senatorsByState <- function(st) {
  for (i in 1:nrow(df)) {
    if (df[i,"party"] == "D") {
      df[i,"party"] <- "Democratic Party"
      } else if (df[i,"party"] == "R") {
        df[i,"party"] <- "Republican Party"
        } else {
          df[i,"party"] <- "Independent Party"
        }
    }
    df.sub <- df %>% filter(df$state == st) %>% select(first_name, last_name, party) 
    names <- str_c(df.sub$first_name, df.sub$last_name, sep = " ")
    pt <- df.sub$party
    name.party <- str_c(names, pt, sep = ", ")
    message <- paste("The senators for", st, "are", name.party[1],
                   "and", name.party[2])
    return(message)
}
# check if it works

senatorsByState('MA')
## [1] "The senators for MA are Edward Markey, Democratic Party and Elizabeth Warren, Democratic Party"
senatorsByState('CA')
## [1] "The senators for CA are Dianne Feinstein, Democratic Party and Alex Padilla, Democratic Party"

# drop rows with NAs
df <- na.omit(df)
# reorder row index
row.names(df) <- NULL
# make df longer by collapse all years into one col
df <- df %>% pivot_longer(cols = !1:4, names_to = "year", values_to = " 
Ratio of female to male youth unemployment rate (% ages 15-24) (modeled ILO estimate)")
# create an age col and impute repeated age values
df$ages <- rep("15-24", 6990)
# rename colnames
colnames(df) <- c("Country_Name", "Country_Code", "Indicator_Name", "Indicator_Code", "Year", "Ratio_Female_Male_Youth_Unemployment_Rate", "Ages")
# separate one col to 5 by assigning corresponding values
df <- df %>% separate(Indicator_Code, into = c("SL", "Unemployment", "age", "Female-Male", "ZS"))
#only unique country names and create a new tibble
## some values in Country_Name are not country name but "High income", "World" but i leave it what it is since it has ratio value in ratio column
country_name <- df[,1:2] %>% distinct()
# View(country_name)
# subset data to create a new tibblt
indicator_data <- df[,c(2,9,10)]

Q5

# create a vector of continent names, 3 names and each repeat for 5 times
continent <- rep(c("Africa", "Asia", "Europe"), each = 5)
# create a new df by filtering specified names from country_name df 
ctr.name.df <- country_name %>% select(Country_Code) %>% filter(Country_Code %in% c("AGO", "NGA", "SSD", "TCD", "GHA", "CHN", "IND", "KOR", "JPN", "IDN", "DEU", "FRA", "ITA", "GRC", "SWE")) 
# reorder the value of country_code column in ctr.name.df accroding to order of continent vector
ctr.name.df$Country_Code <- c("AGO", "NGA", "SSD", "TCD", "GHA", "CHN", "IND", "KOR", "JPN", "IDN", "DEU", "FRA", "ITA", "GRC", "SWE")
# create a new column in ctr.name.df from continent vector 
ctr.name.df$continent <- continent
#join 2 tibbles created above by countr_code and filter for recent 20 years
joined_df <- inner_join(ctr.name.df, indicator_data, c("Country_Code"="Country_Code")) %>% filter(Year %in% 2000:2020)
# create a reference table
indicator_data_filtered <- indicator_data %>% filter(Country_Code %in% c("AGO", "NGA", "SSD", "TCD", "GHA", "CHN", "IND", "KOR", "JPN", "IDN", "DEU", "FRA", "ITA", "GRC", "SWE")) %>% filter(Year %in% 2000:2020)
# check if length of column of joined_df is same as reference
length(joined_df$Country_Code) == length(indicator_data_filtered$Country_Code)
## [1] TRUE
# create line plot faceted by continent and each grouped by country codes
joined_df %>% ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=Ratio_Female_Male_Youth_Unemployment_Rate, group = Country_Code)) +
  geom_line(aes(col=Country_Code)) +
  labs(title = "Ratio of Female to Male Youth Unemployment Rate", x = "Year", y = "Ratio") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=seq(2000, 2020, 4)) +
  facet_wrap(~continent)

## An obvious visual difference among 3 continents, the variances within each continent is lowest in Asia while Africa and Europe varied largely. In terms of trend, there is a pattern where Asian keep  quite constant while Europe demonstrated an overall decrease in recent years since 2008. It is challenging to make conclusive remark and it is hard to predict due to each country here showed different trend.
